default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultWeakness of external auditdefault&#xa0;
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUNISON is concerned that external audit of council procurement decisions and expenditure is weak and that there is an absence of effective mechanisms to review external audit inadequacies. 
default&#xa0;default8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Audit Commission is being disbanded and external audit for councils in England now rests in the hands of ‘self-regulating’ accountancy firms – many of the same firms which have been 
defaultcriticised
default by the Public Accounts Committee for their activities in helping corporate clients dodge taxes
default.
default&#xa0;defaultValue for money - Major contract failure and procurement models that create additional riskdefault&#xa0;
default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecent trends in public sector procurement place reliance on bidders to work out the detail of service design and delivery and calculate the costs – variously referred to as ‘outcomes-based commissioning’, ‘enabling’, ‘thin client’, ‘intelligent client’ and ‘light client’.  Andy 
defaultMudd
default from the Association of Public Service Excellence (APSE) has highlighted how the risks and complexity of working out the necessary ‘inputs’ are increasingly being left to the bidders.
default  
default&#xa0;
default10.
default 
defaultRecent examples West Coast Main Line (Department for Transport), G4S (LOCOG) and allegations of fraud by the Ministry of Justice against SERCO and G4S cast serious doubt on the likelihood that this form of commissioning can deliver best value or transfer risk. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPower imbalancedefault&#xa0;
default11.
default 
default 
defaultUNISON is concerned about the number of instances where the balance of power within complex arrangements is inappropriately weighted towards the private sector and against the public interest. 
defaultThis is largely due to the 
defaultloss of in-house capacity, the development of ‘company towns’ (where the local economy becomes excessively reliant on the contractor’s presence), and the threat of legal action by contractors
default. 
defaultSee example of Liverpool and Southwest One examples in Appendix 1
default. 
defaultValue for money through indefault – defaultsourcingdefault default&#xa0;default12.
default 
defaultThe 
defaultincreases in contract failings have
default led a growing number of local authorities to take the decision to bring privatised services back in-house.
default&#xa0;
default13.
default 
defaultA study
default for UNISON carried out by APSE found that o
defaultut of 140 survey respondents, 57% had either brought a service back in-house, were in the
default 
defaultprocess of 
defaultinsourcing
default or were considering doing so. A need to improve efficiency and reduce service costs was the most frequent key reason for 
defaultinsourcing
default with almost 60% of respondents citing it. After cost, 44% of respondents said a need to improve service quality was critical to the decision to 
defaultinsource
default. The research found that councils of all sizes, locations and political complexions were represented among those deciding to 
defaultinsource
default. 
defaultInsourcing
default was regarded as a means of delivering efficiency savings in the face of mounting budgetary pressure. 
defaultCut-price procurement and the effect on quality: the damage in social care default&#xa0;
default14.
default 
defaultIt is clear that in some areas of local authority expenditure the twin pressures of rising demand for services and funding cuts have created a drive by councils to secure cost-cutting at the expense of service quality. Nowhere is this more prominent than in social care. UNISON has been at the forefront of campaigning to highlight the 
defaultalarming decline in the quality of care that users receive.
default&#xa0;
default15.
default 
defaultUNISON research based on 
defaultFoI
default data from councils in England, Wales and Scotland found that 81% of councils commission from homecare providers where they do not guarantee providers specific hours from one week to the next. This enables councils to drive down the costs they incur as a result of fluctuations in care need. But it fuels the use of zero hours contracts for homecare workers. As the Minister for Care Norman Lamb has stated: 
default“
defaultThe idea of a zero hours contract is in most circumstances completely incompatible with a model of high quality care in which the individual really gets to know their care worker
default.”
default&#xa0;
default16.
default 
defaultThe consequences of this cut-price approach by councils in the homecare sector were encapsulated in the recent Government-commissioned Cavendish Review which stated that:
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultIt will not be possible to build a sustainable, caring, integrated health and social care system on the backs of domiciliary care workers who have to travel long distances on zero hours contracts, to reach people who have to see multiple different faces each week... The advent of zero hours contracts, fee cuts and no payment for travel time is making it financially prohibitive for some domiciliary care workers to struggle on. Attrition rates are already dangerously high: and they will only increase when carers feel that they can no longer even give good care.”
default&#xa0;
default17.
default 
defaultA growing number of councils are recognising that the quality and reliability of privatised homecare has become unacceptable. 
defaultThese developments in homecare have led UNISON to establish our T
defaultime to Care 
defaultcampaign which asks councils to sign up to an ‘ethical care charter’ to commission homecare in line with a core set of baseline standards including non-use of 15-minute visits, ensuring payment of travel time, non-use of zero hours contracts and proper training and support for staff to raise concerns about care standards.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultProcurement from the community and voluntary sectordefault&#xa0;default18.
default 
defaultUNISON represents more than 60,000 members working in the community and voluntary sector – a large proportion of whom work in services commissioned by local government.
default&#xa0;
default19.
default 
defaultUNISON is seeing a rise in consortia bidding for contracts instead of just individual charities. However, these are large and expensive exercises to engage in, and often a large private contractor will be the principle bidder while work flowing to the charities will be sub-contracted.
default&#xa0;
default This has led to the phenomenon of the profitable work being 
defaultcreamed off by the contractor and charities left to deliver  services at bargain basement prices, which are sometimes loss making.
default&#xa0;
default It also means charities having to squeeze down even further on the pay and terms and conditions of staff, and increasingly using zero-hour contracts
default.
default&#xa0;defaultUNISON recommendations on defaultlocal government defaultprocurementdefault&#xa0;default20.
default 
defaultTo address the current concerns around procurement practices UNISON has submitted a set of recommendations to the CLG select committee
default which we would also like the PASC to consider as part of this inquiry in to the governments public service reform programme. See section 2 in Appendix 
default&#xa0;
defaultUK transposition of the defaultEU Procurement Ddefaultirective and reserved contracts for defaultmutualsdefault21.
default 
defaultUNISON has concerns over some provisions in the forthcoming EU procurement directive 
defaultwhich we would like the committee to consider as part of the ongoing inquiry into open public services. These are set out in section 3 Appendix 1 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultQ2: Does opening up the public services to alternative providers improve customer choice, defaultdiversity in local defaultservices and accountability?default&#xa0;defaultNHSdefault&#xa0;default22.
default 
defaultUNISON remains concerned that the choice agenda has been too narrowly focused and too easily equates patients with consumers.
default&#xa0;
default23.
default 
defaultThere is a distinction to be made between real choice and the artificial creation of markets in the health service. When it comes to areas such as maternity or end of life, there is a real choice between different clinical or lifestyle approaches. In other areas, the move to an Any Qualified Provider system of service provision is more about creating a market with opportunities for new entrants from outside the NHS, with no evidence that this form of provider plurality increases the quality of care or patient experience, or that patients want it. 
default&#xa0;
default24.
default 
defaultDavid Boyle’s “Barriers to Choice Review” produced for the government is very instructive in this regards. He found that public support for choice of hospitals is ambiguous and that proximity to home remains the most important factor for patients when choosing which hospital to have their treatment in.
default Boyle has rightly noted that choice has been too closely tied with competition and the concept of “contestability”, which has led to the debate over choice being dominated by ideology rather than what is actually best for patients, parents or service users.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultDecentralisationdefault and diversitydefault&#xa0;
default25.
default 
defaultWhilst the
default restructuring of the NHS appears to be based on 
defaultde
defaultcentralisation with 
defaultcommissioning with clinical commissioning groups now taking the le
defaultad, 
defaultNHS England (the new commissioning board) still wields the most power, both over the CCGs and more generally within the NHS. 
defaultThus power in 
defaultWhitehall, in actual fact
default remains based on 
defaulta c
defaultentralised top-down approach and 
defaultforcing CCGs to put a number of their services out to Any Qualified Provider, when we know that most CCGs would muc
defaulth rather avoid this route. 
default&#xa0;
default26.
default 
defaultUNISON has already demonstrated in numerous submissions with the Health and Social Care 
defaultAct (
default2012) that 
defaultopening up public services does not necessarily improve the options for service users. For example, the development of private sector monopolies (or oligopolies) where services have been 
defaultand are being privatised is likely to encourage 
defaultplayers within the market 
defaultto merge, 
defaultleaving a few big non-public sector providers where previously there were a few b
defaultig public sector providers. T
defaulthe NHS the Competition Commission recently chastised the priva
defaultte hospitals sector on similar grounds
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default27.
default 
defaultUNISON is concerned that 
defaultthe recent reforms to 
defaultmarketise
default the NHS and the failure to fund the service adequately has led to the rationing of services becoming increasingly prevalent. This has meant that many patients are now faced with the option of paying to go private or having their care limited / co
defaultmpromised. Evidence of this is referenced at the footnote 
default&#xa0;
default28.
default 
defaultUNISON believes that the a
defaultccountability
default in health services with the new structures in commissioning 
defaulthas effectively removed the ultimate responsibility for the NHS from the (democratically elected) Secretary of State and handed it to the NHS commissioning board, an unelected super-
defaultquango
default. The attempt to remedy the lack of local democracy in the NHS through Health and Wellbeing Boards, although a good 
defaultidea
default is insufficiently strong to do this: HWBs lack the power to veto commissioning decisions, and they need have only one elected councillor among their number.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultQ3.default How can risks be reduced in defaultOpen access to public services under alternative forms of ownershipdefault?default&#xa0;default29.
