defaultUNISON has concerns that currently in the drive to open up public services and ensure open access 
defaultand minimise 
defaultrisks of alternative forms of ownership, provision and accountability
default, basic statutory duties are not being fulfilled therefore diminishing the empowerment of stakeholders and citizens and service users.
default 
defaultWe 
defaultgive the example
defaults
default of
default Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) and Ministry of Justice Probation Reforms
default&#xa0;defaultPolice and Crime Commissionersdefault (PCCs)default&#xa0;default30.
default 
default PCCs  are 
defaultunder a new statutory obligation to publish a wide range of information to their electorates. The relevant statutory instrument is: The Elected Local Policing Bodies (Specified Information) (Amendment Order) 2012 
default&#xa0;
default31.
default 
defaultIn relation to opening up privatised police services to scrutiny, the Order promised that PCCs would have to publish:
default&#xa0;
default32.
default 
defaultThe Order requires that all the above information to be published as soon as practicable after it becomes available to the PCC.PCCs were elected in November 2012 and 10 months later UNISON can find no evidence that any of the above information has been published by PCCs. 
default&#xa0;
default33.
default 
defaultG4S currently operates one of the biggest privatised police contracts in the UK for Lincolnshire Police. In April of 2013, the company and the Lincolnshire PCC published a glossy report which made a number of claims regarding the performance of the contract. Unfortunately, in the absence of the information required to be published under the above statutory order, neither Lincolnshire voters, nor other interested parties can scrutinise the company’s claims. 
default&#xa0;
default34.
default 
defaultUNISON asks what the Government is doing to make its requirement on PCCs to publish commercial contracts, work in practice
default as part of its public service reform programme empowering the citizen and service users?
defaultMinistry of Justice Probation Reformsdefault35.
default 
defaultUnder the Ministry of Justice ‘Transforming Rehabilitation’ proposals
default, local probation services will be removed in their entirety from any potential for open access or accountability. 20 years ago, Probation was run as a local service by committees of the upper tier local authority, with local councillors on their boards and 20% or so of funding coming directly from the local authority. Local magistrates also sat on the committee. 
default&#xa0;
default36.
default 
defaultSince that time, successive governments have stripped out this local representation and funding,  and when Probation Trusts were created in 2007 all vestiges of local authority representation were finally removed. 
default&#xa0;
default37.
default 
defaultIn 2013, the Justice Secretary Chris Grayling announced radical reforms of the Probation Service to abolish the 35 local Probation Trusts, replacing them with 21 government companies, which are to be sold to the private sector in October 2014. Not only will the reduction in local entities from 35 to 21 destroy the co-
defaultterminosity
default of Probation areas with police force boundaries, but the handing of probation services to the private sector by the Secretary of State as the single commissioner and client removes at a stroke any pretence at localism or accountability for the Probation Service.
default&#xa0;
default38.
default 
default 
defaultThe creation of these new 21 private entities to run probation services undermines the public and citizens access to how their local police and justice services should be run. It undermines the ability of the elected 
defaultPolice and Crime Commissioner
defaults to be accountable in their public role to be able to influence locally the 
defaultcommissioning 
defaultof 
defaultpo
defaultlice and local justice probation services.
default&#xa0;
default39.
default 
default Although UNISON notes that 
defaultthe Justice Secretary
default has agreed
default to create a boar
defaultd to allow PCCs
default to influence the commissioning process
default it is not clear how much commissioning decision making  
defaultpower the b
defaultoard will have in the 
defaultin the contract award of 
defaultthe 21 private companies.
default&#xa0;
default40.
default 
defaultUNISON has no evidence that these new structures will 
defaultre-introduce any localism
default, open access for grass roots communities to influence local probation services through their 
defaultelected PCC
default or 
defaultprovide sound 
defaultaccounta
defaultbility into the process of how the 21 private companies will operate public probation services, particularly as the Secretary of State 
defaultremain
defaults
